#Text=Thomas Dyche
#Text=Reverend Thomas Dyche ( died c. 1733 ) was an English schoolmaster and lexicographer ( probably ) from Ashbourne , Derbyshire .
#Text=He published a number of books on the English language including one thought to be the first English book published in Asia . [ 3 ]
#Text=He is remembered for his reference books and his contribution to pronunciation . [ 4 ]
#Text=Dyche 's New General English Dictionary was in print from 1735 to 1798 and went through eighteen editions . [ 4 ]
#Text=Biography
#Text=Dyche was educated at Ashbourne free school , Derbyshire , under the Rev. William Hardestee ( dedication of Vocabularium Latiale , 5th edition ) .
#Text=He subsequently took orders , and moved to London .
#Text=In 1708 he was keeping school in Dean Street , Fetter Lane , but some time after 1710 he obtained , the mastership of the free school at Stratford Bow .
#Text=In 1716 , Dyche 's book A Guide to the English Tongue was being published by the linguist Bartholomaeus Ziegenbalg in Tharangambadi .
#Text=This is believed to be the first book published in English in Asia . [ 3 ]
#Text=In 1719 he rashly attempted to expose in print the peculations of the notorious John Ward of Hackney in discharge of his [ Ward 's ] trust about repairing Dagnam Breach .
#Text=Thereupon Ward sued Dyche for libel , and at the trial , 18 June 1719 , was awarded sizeable damages . [ 5 ]
#Text=Dyche seems to have died between 1731 and 1735 .
#Text=Dyche 's New General English Dictionary was in print from 1735 to 1798 and went through eighteen editions . [ 4 ]
#Text=His work identified as " conspicuous " was A Guide to the English Tongue , which was in print from its first publication in 1709 through a 48th edition in 1780 and a final print in 1830 .
#Text=This work differed from other similar works in that it emphasized pronunciation .

#Text=Within the book words were sorted into groups where words with two syllables were further sub-divided into those that emphasized the first syllable and to those that emphasized the second syllable . [ 4 ]
#Text=Sorting words by sound and then in order led to lists that attracted comment , e.g. , hiss , kiss , miss , piss , bliss . [ 6 ]
#Text=This work was a good foundation for his later work on pronunciation in English , which defined over 20,000 words .
#Text=Although this work was called A Dictionary of Words us 'd in the English Tongue ...
#Text=it was a guide to spelling and pronunciation .
#Text=The work included a number of suggestions for changing the spelling of various words and these suggestions were in time accepted into modern English . [ 4 ]
#Text=This work went through seven editions between 1723 and 1756 .
#Text=Major works
#Text=Vocabularium Latiale , or a Latin Vocabulary , in two parts , 8vo , London , 1708 or 1709 ; 5th edition , 8vo , London , 1728 ; 6th edition , .
#Text=8vo , London , 1735 .
#Text=A Guide to the English Tongue , in two parts , 8vo , London , . 1709 ; 2nd edition , 8vo , London , 1710 ; 14th edition , 12mo , London , 1729 .

#Text=This , the forerunner of similar compendiums by Dilworth , Fenning , and Mavor , had the honour of being ushered into the world with lines addressed to my ingenious Friend the Author by laureate Tate .
#Text=Another less famous poet , by name John Williams , enthusiastically declares
#Text=This just essay you have perform 'd so well , Records will shew ' twas Dyche first taught to spell .

#Text=The Spelling Dictionary ; or , A Collection of all the common Words and Proper Names made use of in the English Tongue , 1st edition , London , 1723 ; 2nd edition revised , 12mo , London , 1725 ; 3rd edition corrected , 12mo , London , 1731 ; 4th edition corrected , with large additions , 12 mo , London , 1737 .
#Text=A New General English Dictionary ; Peculiarly calculated for the Use and Improvement Of such as are unacquainted with the Learned Languages , 1st edition .
#Text=London : Richard Ware , 1735 .
#Text=The publisher added this helpful note to the title page :
#Text=" Originally begun by the late Reverend Mr. Thomas Dyche , ... And now finish 'd by William Pardon , Gent . "
#Text=Many editions were subsequently published .
#Text=A French version , with plates , by Père [ Rev. ] Esprit Pezenas , appeared in two vols. 4to , Avignon , 1756 .
#Text=Dyche was also author of ' The Youth 's Guide to the Latin Tongue , ' and ' Fables of Phaedrus , rendered into familiar English .
